Explainable High-Resolution Cross-Eukaryotic Translation Initiation Site PredictionThis repository contains the training and evaluation pipeline for a hybrid bioinformatics model designed to predict eukaryotic translation initiation sites (start codons). It fetches Pan-Eukaryotic training data directly from NCBI via Entrez, constructs a Position Weight Matrix (PWM) and codon-level emission model, and benchmarks predictive accuracy using a novel "Biological Gatekeeper" architecture.FeaturesAutomated Data Fetching: Directly pulls training genomes and Chromosome IV benchmark data using BioPython's Entrez module.Pan-Eukaryotic PWM Generation: Calculates upstream positional frequencies to score potential promoter regions.Codon-Level Tokenization: Encodes sequences into a strict 65-token vocabulary for downstream state emission analysis.Comprehensive Benchmarking: Evaluates models using Accuracy, Precision, Recall, F1, MCC, Mean Absolute Error (MAE), Specificity, and exact start-site matching percentages.Automated Visualizations: Generates robust performance dashboards, ROC curves, and confusion matrices.Architecture ComparisonThe script evaluates and compares two distinct decoder approaches against a baseline 3-State HMM:DecoderDescriptionFiltering Mechanismv1 (PWM Only)Unrestricted PromotersEvaluates the 50bp upstream sequence of every ATG token and selects the highest scoring candidate. No thresholds applied.v2 (Biological Gatekeeper)Dual Hard-FiltersApplies a dynamic PWM threshold (≥ -3.0) and enforces a minimum projected CDS length (≥ 135 bp) to suppress sORF false positives.DependenciesEnsure you have Python 3.8+ installed. The pipeline requires the following packages:biopythonscikit-learnnumpypandasmatplotlibseabornYou can install the required libraries using pip:Bashpip install biopython scikit-learn numpy pandas matplotlib seaborn
Important: Update the Entrez.email variable in the script with a valid email address to comply with NCBI's usage guidelines and prevent your IP from being blocked.UsageThe script is executed via the command line. By default, it looks for an existing trained model to bypass the lengthy NCBI data-fetching and training process. If the model file is not found, it will automatically train a new one using training_sources.json.Run the benchmark with the default model path (model.pkl):Bashpython benchmark.py
Specify a custom path for saving or loading the model:Bashpython benchmark.py --model_file my_custom_model.pkl
Pipeline OutputsAfter running the inference and evaluation steps on the test set, the script will generate the following artifacts in your working directory:Output ArtifactTypeDescriptionmodel.pklBinarySerialized model data containing the pwm_logo, codon_vocab, emissions, and log_emissions.v2_comparison_table.csvDataTabular breakdown of core classification metrics comparing the baseline, v1, and v2 decoders.v2_comparison_dashboard.pngVisualHigh-resolution bar charts highlighting the metric deltas (Δ) between v1 and v2 alongside MAE comparisons.performance_diagnostics.pngVisualConfusion matrices and ROC curves (with calculated AUC) for both v1 and v2 decoders.


